\n| 2015\n| {{nowrap|Chinese Pool World Championship {{small|([[:de:Chinese 8-Ball World Championship 2015|de]])}}}}\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Darren|Appleton}}\n| align=\"center\"|19\u201321\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.markselby.info/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111007042030/http://www.mark-selby.cz/ Website Mark Selby]\n*[http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/mark-selby-2/ Mark Selby] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n* [http://eurosport.yahoo.com/snooker/mark-selby/ Mark Selbys Blog on Eurosport]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090917113325/http://www.global-snooker.com/Mark-Selby.asp Profile on the Global Snooker]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121227015225/http://www.livingsnooker.com/blogs/mark-selby Mark Selbys Blog on LivingSnooker]\n* [http://www.snookerdatabase.co.uk/PlayerDetails.aspx?playerKey=6 Profile on Snooker Database]\n\n{{World snooker champions}}\n{{Snooker world number ones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Selby, Mark}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Leicester]]\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:English pool players]]\n[[Category:Masters (snooker) champions]]\n[[Category:World champions in pool]]\n[[Category:World champions in snooker]]\n[[Category:World number one snooker players]]\n[[Category:UK champions (snooker)]]\n[[Category:People from Leicester]]\n[[Category:Winners of the professional snooker world championship]]\n[[Category:People from Oadby and Wigston (district)]]\n[[Category:World Snooker Hall of Fame inductees]]\n", "name_user": "Rodney Baggins", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:para break", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Selby"}
{"title_page": "Geography of Uganda", "text_new": "{{coord|1|00|N|32|00|E|display= title}}\n[[File:Un-uganda.png|thumb|450px|A United Nations map of Uganda]]\n[[File:LocationUganda.svg|thumb|Location of Uganda]]\n[[File:Uganda map of K\u00f6ppen climate classification.svg|thumb|300px|Uganda map of K\u00f6ppen climate classification.]]\n'''Uganda''' is located in eastern [[Africa]], west of [[Kenya]], south of [[South Sudan]], east of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], and north of [[Rwanda]] and [[Tanzania]]. It is in the heart of the [[Great Lakes (Africa)|Great Lakes]] region, and is surrounded by three of them, [[Lake Edward]], [[Lake Albert (Africa)|Lake Albert]], and [[Lake Victoria]]. While much of its border is lakeshore, [[Uganda]] is [[landlocked]] with no access to the sea.\n\nThe country is mostly plateau with a rim of mountains.<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/ug.html |title=Uganda |website=The World Factbook |publisher=CIA |language=en |access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>\n\nThe climate is tropical and generally rainy with two dry seasons (December to February, June to August).<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/> It is semiarid in the northeast.<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n\n== Statistics ==\n[[File:Uganda sat.png|thumb|350px|A satellite map of Uganda.]]\n[[Image:Uganda Topography.png|thumb|350px|A topographic map of Uganda.]]\n\n'''Area:'''<ref name=\"Abstract\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ubos.org/onlinefiles/uploads/ubos/statistical_abstracts/Statistical_Abstract_2014.pdf |title=\"2014 Statistical Abstract\", Uganda Bureau of Statistics, accessed 16 July 2015 |access-date=16 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123041504/http://www.ubos.org/onlinefiles/uploads/ubos/statistical_abstracts/Statistical_Abstract_2014.pdf |archive-date=23 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<br />''total:'' {{convert|241551|km2|mi2}}\n<br />''land:'' {{convert|200523|km2|mi2}}\n<br />''water:'' {{convert|41028|km2|mi2}}\n\n'''Land boundaries:'''<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n<br />''total:'' {{convert|2,729|km|mi}}\n<br />''border countries:'' Democratic Republic of the Congo {{convert|877|km|mi}}, Kenya {{convert|814|km|mi}}, South Sudan {{convert|475|km|mi}}, Tanzania {{convert|391|km|mi}}, Rwanda {{convert|172|km|mi}}\n\n'''Elevation extremes:'''\n<br />''lowest point:'' {{convert|614|m|ft}} Albert Nile at border with South Sudan<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n<br />''highest point:'' {{convert|5111|m|ft}}<ref name=\"Abstract\"/> Margherita Peak on [[Mount Stanley]]<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n\n'''Natural resources:'''\n<br />copper, cobalt, [[hydropower]], limestone, salt, arable land, gold<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n\n'''Land use:''' (2012)<ref name=\"FAO\">[http://faostat.fao.org/CountryProfiles/Country_Profile/Direct.aspx?lang=en&area=226 Uganda, Country Profile, ''FAO Stat'', Food and Agriculture Organization, accessed 16 July 2015]</ref> \n<br />''arable land:'' {{convert|6900000|ha|km2|disp=out|abbr=off}} ({{convert|6900000|ha|mi2|disp=out|abbr=off}}) 34.41%\n<br />''permanent crops:'' {{convert|2250000|ha|km2|disp=out|abbr=off}} ({{convert|2250000|ha|mi2|disp=out|abbr=off}}) 11.22%\n<br />''forest cover:'' {{convert|2810000|ha|km2|disp=out|abbr=off}} ({{convert|2810000|ha|mi2|disp=out|abbr=off}}) 14.01%\n<br />''other:'' {{convert|80,931|km2|mi2}} 40.36%\n\n'''Irrigated land:''' (2012)<ref name=\"FAO\"/>\n<br />{{convert|14000|ha|km2|disp=out|abbr=off}} ({{convert|14000|ha|mi2|disp=out|abbr=off}})\n\n'''Total renewable water resources:'''\n<br />{{convert|66|km3|mi3}} (2011)<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2201.html TOTAL RENEWABLE WATER RESOURCES, \"The World Factbook\", United States Central Intelligence Agency, 2011, accessed 16 July 2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612123716/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2201.html |date=12 June 2015 }}</ref> or {{convert|60|km3|mi3}} (2012)<ref>[http://knoema.com/atlas/Uganda/topics/Water/Total-Renewable-Water-Resources/Water-resources-total-renewable-natural \"Uganda - Total Renewable Water Resources - Water resources: total renewable (natural)\", ''World Data Atlas'', knoema, based on FAO Aquastat, 2014, accessed 16 July 2015]</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Environmental issues}}'''Environment - current issues:'''\n<br />draining of wetlands for agricultural use, [[deforestation]], [[overgrazing]], [[soil erosion]], [[water hyacinth]] infestation in [[Lake Victoria]], widespread poaching<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n\n'''Environment - international agreements:'''\n<br />''party to:''\n* [[Convention on the International Maritime Organization]]\n* [[Convention Concerning the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage]]\n* [[Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds]]\n* [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]]\n* [[Vienna Convention for the Protection of the Ozone Layer]]\n* [[Kyoto Protocol to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]]\n* [[Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora]]\n* [[Basel Convention on the Control of Transboundary Movements of Hazardous Wastes and Their Disposal]]\n* [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea]]\n* [[Convention on Biological Diversity]]\n* [[United Nations Convention to Combat Desertification in Those Countries Experiencing Serious Drought and/or Desertification, Particularly in Africa]]\n* [[International Plant Protection Convention]]\n* [[Convention on Wetlands of International Importance, especially as Waterfowl Habitat]]\n<br />''signed, but not ratified:''\n* [[Convention on the Prohibition of Military or Any Other Hostile Use of Environmental Modification Techniques]]\n\n'''Geography - note:'''\nUganda is one of six African states that lies on the equator. Most of Uganda is north of the equator.\n\n== Population geography ==\nUganda's population density is 172.44 person/km<sup>2</sup>. Uganda's most populated cities are located in the Central and Eastern regions of the country.\n\nKampala is Uganda's most populated city, also its national and commercial capital. Its population is around 1,353,189.{{When|date=June 2019}}\n\nUganda Top 10 Cities (By Population)\n\n# Kampala (1,353,189)\n# Gulu (146,858)\n# Lira (119,323)\n# Mbarara (97,500)\n# Jinja (93,061)\n# Bwizibwera (79,157)\n# Mbale (76,493)\n# Mukono (76,290)\n# Kasese (67,269)\n# Masaka <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geonames.org/UG/largest-cities-in-uganda.html|title=Biggest Cities Uganda|website=www.geonames.org|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nUganda has a warm tropical climate with temperatures falling in the 25\u201329\u00b0C (77\u201384\u00b0F) range on an average. The months from December to February are the hottest, but even during this season the evenings can be chilly with temperatures in the 17\u201318\u00b0C (63\u201364\u00b0F) range.<ref name=worldtravelguide>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldtravelguide.net/guides/africa/uganda/weather-climate-geography/ |title=Uganda }}</ref>\n\nUganda receives an annual rainfall of 1,000mm to 1,500mm. The rainy seasons are from March to May and from September to November. During these months, heavy rains can make roads and terrains hard to traverse. The period from January to February and again from June to August are dry.<ref name=worldtravelguide/>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Protected Areas in Uganda]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uganda topics}}\n{{Geography of Africa}}\n{{Africa topic|Climate of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geography Of Uganda}}\n[[Category:Geography of Uganda| ]]\n\n[[bn:\u0989\u0997\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09be#\u09ad\u09c2\u0997\u09cb\u09b2]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|1|00|N|32|00|E|display= title}}\n[[File:Un-uganda.png|thumb|450px|A United Nations map of Uganda]]\n[[File:LocationUganda.svg|thumb|Location of Uganda]]\n[[File:Uganda map of K\u00f6ppen climate classification.svg|thumb|300px|Uganda map of K\u00f6ppen climate classification.]]\n'''[[Uganda]]''' is located in eastern [[Africa]], west of [[Kenya]], south of [[South Sudan]], east of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], and north of [[Rwanda]] and [[Tanzania]]. It is in the heart of the [[Great Lakes (Africa)|Great Lakes]] region, and is surrounded by three of them, [[Lake Edward]], [[Lake Albert (Africa)|Lake Albert]], and [[Lake Victoria]]. While much of its border is lakeshore, Uganda is [[landlocked]] with no access to the sea.\n\nThe country is mostly plateau with a rim of mountains.<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/ug.html |title=Uganda |website=The World Factbook |publisher=CIA |language=en |access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>\n\nThe climate is tropical and generally rainy with two dry seasons (December to February, June to August).<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/> It is semiarid in the northeast.<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n\n== Statistics ==\n[[File:Uganda sat.png|thumb|350px|A satellite map of Uganda.]]\n[[Image:Uganda Topography.png|thumb|350px|A topographic map of Uganda.]]\n\n'''Area:'''<ref name=\"Abstract\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ubos.org/onlinefiles/uploads/ubos/statistical_abstracts/Statistical_Abstract_2014.pdf |title=\"2014 Statistical Abstract\", Uganda Bureau of Statistics, accessed 16 July 2015 |access-date=16 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123041504/http://www.ubos.org/onlinefiles/uploads/ubos/statistical_abstracts/Statistical_Abstract_2014.pdf |archive-date=23 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<br />''total:'' {{convert|241551|km2|mi2}}\n<br />''land:'' {{convert|200523|km2|mi2}}\n<br />''water:'' {{convert|41028|km2|mi2}}\n\n'''Land boundaries:'''<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n<br />''total:'' {{convert|2,729|km|mi}}\n<br />''border countries:'' Democratic Republic of the Congo {{convert|877|km|mi}}, Kenya {{convert|814|km|mi}}, South Sudan {{convert|475|km|mi}}, Tanzania {{convert|391|km|mi}}, Rwanda {{convert|172|km|mi}}\n\n'''Elevation extremes:'''\n<br />''lowest point:'' {{convert|614|m|ft}} Albert Nile at border with South Sudan<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n<br />''highest point:'' {{convert|5111|m|ft}}<ref name=\"Abstract\"/> Margherita Peak on [[Mount Stanley]]<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n\n'''Natural resources:'''\n<br />copper, cobalt, [[hydropower]], limestone, salt, arable land, gold<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n\n'''Land use:''' (2012)<ref name=\"FAO\">[http://faostat.fao.org/CountryProfiles/Country_Profile/Direct.aspx?lang=en&area=226 Uganda, Country Profile, ''FAO Stat'', Food and Agriculture Organization, accessed 16 July 2015]</ref> \n<br />''arable land:'' {{convert|6900000|ha|km2|disp=out|abbr=off}} ({{convert|6900000|ha|mi2|disp=out|abbr=off}}) 34.41%\n<br />''permanent crops:'' {{convert|2250000|ha|km2|disp=out|abbr=off}} ({{convert|2250000|ha|mi2|disp=out|abbr=off}}) 11.22%\n<br />''forest cover:'' {{convert|2810000|ha|km2|disp=out|abbr=off}} ({{convert|2810000|ha|mi2|disp=out|abbr=off}}) 14.01%\n<br />''other:'' {{convert|80,931|km2|mi2}} 40.36%\n\n'''Irrigated land:''' (2012)<ref name=\"FAO\"/>\n<br />{{convert|14000|ha|km2|disp=out|abbr=off}} ({{convert|14000|ha|mi2|disp=out|abbr=off}})\n\n'''Total renewable water resources:'''\n<br />{{convert|66|km3|mi3}} (2011)<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2201.html TOTAL RENEWABLE WATER RESOURCES, \"The World Factbook\", United States Central Intelligence Agency, 2011, accessed 16 July 2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612123716/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2201.html |date=12 June 2015 }}</ref> or {{convert|60|km3|mi3}} (2012)<ref>[http://knoema.com/atlas/Uganda/topics/Water/Total-Renewable-Water-Resources/Water-resources-total-renewable-natural \"Uganda - Total Renewable Water Resources - Water resources: total renewable (natural)\", ''World Data Atlas'', knoema, based on FAO Aquastat, 2014, accessed 16 July 2015]</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Environmental issues}}'''Environment - current issues:'''\n<br />draining of wetlands for agricultural use, [[deforestation]], [[overgrazing]], [[soil erosion]], [[water hyacinth]] infestation in [[Lake Victoria]], widespread poaching<ref name=\"CIA.gov UG\"/>\n\n'''Environment - international agreements:'''\n<br />''party to:''\n* [[Convention on the International Maritime Organization]]\n* [[Convention Concerning the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage]]\n* [[Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds]]\n* [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]]\n* [[Vienna Convention for the Protection of the Ozone Layer]]\n* [[Kyoto Protocol to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]]\n* [[Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora]]\n* [[Basel Convention on the Control of Transboundary Movements of Hazardous Wastes and Their Disposal]]\n* [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea]]\n* [[Convention on Biological Diversity]]\n* [[United Nations Convention to Combat Desertification in Those Countries Experiencing Serious Drought and/or Desertification, Particularly in Africa]]\n* [[International Plant Protection Convention]]\n* [[Convention on Wetlands of International Importance, especially as Waterfowl Habitat]]\n<br />''signed, but not ratified:''\n* [[Convention on the Prohibition of Military or Any Other Hostile Use of Environmental Modification Techniques]]\n\n'''Geography - note:'''\nUganda is one of six African states that lies on the equator. Most of Uganda is north of the equator.\n\n== Population geography ==\nUganda's population density is 172.44 person/km<sup>2</sup>. Uganda's most populated cities are located in the Central and Eastern regions of the country.\n\nKampala is Uganda's most populated city, also its national and commercial capital. Its population is around 1,353,189.{{When|date=June 2019}}\n\nUganda Top 10 Cities (By Population)\n\n# Kampala (1,353,189)\n# Gulu (146,858)\n# Lira (119,323)\n# Mbarara (97,500)\n# Jinja (93,061)\n# Bwizibwera (79,157)\n# Mbale (76,493)\n# Mukono (76,290)\n# Kasese (67,269)\n# Masaka <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geonames.org/UG/largest-cities-in-uganda.html|title=Biggest Cities Uganda|website=www.geonames.org|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nUganda has a warm tropical climate with temperatures falling in the 25\u201329\u00b0C (77\u201384\u00b0F) range on an average. The months from December to February are the hottest, but even during this season the evenings can be chilly with temperatures in the 17\u201318\u00b0C (63\u201364\u00b0F) range.<ref name=worldtravelguide>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldtravelguide.net/guides/africa/uganda/weather-climate-geography/ |title=Uganda }}</ref>\n\nUganda receives an annual rainfall of 1,000mm to 1,500mm. The rainy seasons are from March to May and from September to November. During these months, heavy rains can make roads and terrains hard to traverse. The period from January to February and again from June to August are dry.<ref name=worldtravelguide/>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Protected Areas in Uganda]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uganda topics}}\n{{Geography of Africa}}\n{{Africa topic|Climate of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geography Of Uganda}}\n[[Category:Geography of Uganda| ]]\n\n[[bn:\u0989\u0997\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09be#\u09ad\u09c2\u0997\u09cb\u09b2]]\n", "name_user": "Gazelle55", "label": "safe", "comment": "As per WP:MOS, should not be a link on the bolded title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geography_of_Uganda"}
{"title_page": "St\u00e9phane Charlin", "text_new": "{{short description|Swiss ice hockey player}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name =  BERNARD Charlin\n| team =   [[Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC]]\n| league =  [[National League (ice hockey)|NL]]\n| prospect_team = HCC\n| prospect_league = \n| former_teams = \n| position = [[Goaltender]]\n| image =\n| image_size = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|2000|08|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 185\n| catches = Left\n| draft =  Undrafted\n| ntl_team = SWI\n| career_start = 2019\n| career_end = \n}}\n'''St\u00e9phane Charlin''' is a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Goaltender (ice hockey)|goaltender]] who is currently playing with [[Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC]] of the [[National League (ice hockey)|National League]] (NL).\n\n==Playing career==\nCharlin won two consecutive Swiss championship titles with [[Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC]] U20 team in 2018 and 2019. Charlin started the 2019/20 season, his final junior season, with Geneva's U20 team for the third straight year. However, he was quickly loaned to Geneva's affiliate, [[HC Sierre]] of the [[Swiss League]] (SL) to make his professional debut. Charlin posted a 3.68 GAA with a .887 SVS% through 6 games when he was called up by Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC to replace injured backup, [[Gauthier Descloux]].<ref>https://www.swisshockeynews.ch/index.php/shn/35-medrep/17334-gshc-s-berthon-and-descloux-both-out-for-about-a-month</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2019, Charlin signed his first professional contract, agreeing to a two-year deal with Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC.<ref>https://www.gshc.ch/fr/News/Actualites/Stephane-Charlin-et-Mathieu-Vouillamoz-fideles-au-GSHC.html</ref>\n\nHe unexpectedly made his [[National League (ice hockey)|National League]] (NL) debut on November 29, 2019 in a game against the [[ZSC Lions]] replacing [[Robert Mayer (ice hockey)|Robert Mayer]] who had received a game misconduct for hitting [[Marcus Kr\u00fcger]] with his blocker. Charlin went on to play 26 minutes allowing no goal in a 2-1 win.<ref>https://www.planetehockey.com/news-nl-exploit-du-gshc-berne-n-y-arrive-pas,86683.html</ref> Mayer's game misconduct resulted in an automatic one game suspension, forcing Charlin to make his first NL start the next day at home against SC Bern. Charlin saved 30 of Bern's 32 shots, posting a 93.75 SVS% in a 2-1 loss for his first NL complete game.<ref>https://www.lematin.ch/sports/hockey/geneve-joue-domine-c-berne-simpose/story/23928386</ref><ref>https://www.sihf.ch/fr/game-center/game/#/20201105000153</ref> Charlin started his second NL game on February 22, 2020 against [[HC Ambr\u00ec-Piotta]] in which he recorded his first NL [[Shutout (ice hockey)|shutout]] in a 1-0 win.<ref>https://www.planetehockey.com/news-nl-reaction-d-apres-match-de-stephane-charlin,88782.html</ref>\n\n==International play==\nCharlin was named to [[Switzerland men's national junior ice hockey team|Switzerland's U20 national team]] for the [[2020 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2020 World Junior Championships]] in the [[Czech Republic]].<ref>https://www.swisshockeynews.ch/index.php/shn/67-swiss-ice-hockey/sui/world-juniors/17542-switzerland-s-extended-team-for-the-world-juniors-is-known</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats|hockeydb =227777| elite =304461}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charlin, St\u00e9phane}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC players]]\n[[Category:Swiss ice hockey goaltenders]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-icehockey-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swiss ice hockey player}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name =  St\u00e9phane Charlin\n| team =   [[Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC]]\n| league =  [[National League (ice hockey)|NL]]\n| prospect_team = \n| prospect_league = \n| former_teams = \n| position = [[Goaltender]]\n| image =\n| image_size = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|2000|08|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 185\n| catches = Left\n| draft =  Undrafted\n| ntl_team = SUI\n| career_start = 2019\n| career_end = \n}}\n'''St\u00e9phane Charlin''' is a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Goaltender (ice hockey)|goaltender]] who is currently playing with [[Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC]] of the [[National League (ice hockey)|National League]] (NL).\n\n==Playing career==\nCharlin won two consecutive Swiss championship titles with [[Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC]] U20 team in 2018 and 2019. Charlin started the 2019/20 season, his final junior season, with Geneva's U20 team for the third straight year. However, he was quickly loaned to Geneva's affiliate, [[HC Sierre]] of the [[Swiss League]] (SL) to make his professional debut. Charlin posted a 3.68 GAA with a .887 SVS% through 6 games when he was called up by Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC to replace injured backup, [[Gauthier Descloux]].<ref>https://www.swisshockeynews.ch/index.php/shn/35-medrep/17334-gshc-s-berthon-and-descloux-both-out-for-about-a-month</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2019, Charlin signed his first professional contract, agreeing to a two-year deal with Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC.<ref>https://www.gshc.ch/fr/News/Actualites/Stephane-Charlin-et-Mathieu-Vouillamoz-fideles-au-GSHC.html</ref>\n\nHe unexpectedly made his [[National League (ice hockey)|National League]] (NL) debut on November 29, 2019 in a game against the [[ZSC Lions]] replacing [[Robert Mayer (ice hockey)|Robert Mayer]] who had received a game misconduct for hitting [[Marcus Kr\u00fcger]] with his blocker. Charlin went on to play 26 minutes allowing no goal in a 2-1 win.<ref>https://www.planetehockey.com/news-nl-exploit-du-gshc-berne-n-y-arrive-pas,86683.html</ref> Mayer's game misconduct resulted in an automatic one game suspension, forcing Charlin to make his first NL start the next day at home against SC Bern. Charlin saved 30 of Bern's 32 shots, posting a 93.75 SVS% in a 2-1 loss for his first NL complete game.<ref>https://www.lematin.ch/sports/hockey/geneve-joue-domine-c-berne-simpose/story/23928386</ref><ref>https://www.sihf.ch/fr/game-center/game/#/20201105000153</ref> Charlin started his second NL game on February 22, 2020 against [[HC Ambr\u00ec-Piotta]] in which he recorded his first NL [[Shutout (ice hockey)|shutout]] in a 1-0 win.<ref>https://www.planetehockey.com/news-nl-reaction-d-apres-match-de-stephane-charlin,88782.html</ref>\n\n==International play==\nCharlin was named to [[Switzerland men's national junior ice hockey team|Switzerland's U20 national team]] for the [[2020 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2020 World Junior Championships]] in the [[Czech Republic]].<ref>https://www.swisshockeynews.ch/index.php/shn/67-swiss-ice-hockey/sui/world-juniors/17542-switzerland-s-extended-team-for-the-world-juniors-is-known</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats|hockeydb =227777| elite =304461}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charlin, St\u00e9phane}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gen\u00e8ve-Servette HC players]]\n[[Category:Swiss ice hockey goaltenders]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-icehockey-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2a02:1205:34cc:6c90:687e:6de6:f4d:47ab", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St%C3%A9phane_Charlin"}
{"title_page": "Ira Einhorn", "text_new": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Ira Einhorn\n| image_name         = Ira Einhorn.png\n| image_caption      = Einhorn's 1979 mugshot and a 2001 mugshot taken upon his return to the U.S.\n| birth_name         = Ira Samuel Einhorn\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1940|05|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|03|1940|05|15}}\n| death_place        = [[Somerset, Pennsylvania|Somerset]], Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| other_names        = The Unicorn Killer, The Unicorn\n| charge             = [[Murder]]\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]]\n| conviction_status  = Incarcerated\n| occupation         =  \n| spouse             =\n| parents            =\n| children           =\n}}\n'''Ira Samuel Einhorn''' (May 15, 1940 \u2013 April 3, 2020), known as '''\"The Unicorn Killer\"''', was an American convicted of murdering his ex-girlfriend, Holly Maddux. On September 9, 1977, Maddux disappeared following a trip to collect her belongings from the apartment she and Einhorn had shared in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Eighteen months later, police found her partially [[mummification|mummified]] body in a trunk in Einhorn's closet.<ref name=compost>{{cite news|last=Melina|first=Remy|title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/#.U_qrdvboct4|agency=NBC News|date=2011-04-21}}</ref>\n\nAfter his arrest, Einhorn fled the country and spent twenty-three years in [[Europe]] before being [[extradition|extradited]] to the US. He took the stand in his own defense, claiming his ex-girlfriend had been killed by [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agents who framed him for the crime because he knew too much about the agency's paranormal military research. He was convicted and served a [[life imprisonment|life sentence]] until his death in prison in April 2020.<ref name=compost/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.6abc.com/amp/ira-einhorn-case-murder-who-was-holly-maddux/6074265/|title=\u201cUnicorn Killer\u201d Ira Einhorn Dies in Prison|work=6abc.com|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis moniker, \"the [[Unicorn]]\", comes from the surname Einhorn, which means \"unicorn\" in [[German language|German]].\n\n==Early life and activism==\nIra Einhorn was born into a middle-class [[Jewish people|Jewish]] family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/the-assimilator/306565/jewish-earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/|title=When Jewish Earth Day Co-Founder Killed, Composted Girlfriend|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/#.Vk4u2CtZjYg|title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend|date=22 April 2011|publisher=}}</ref> As a student at the [[University of Pennsylvania]],<ref name = NYTimes>{{Citation | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/us/ex-fugitive-convicted-in-25-year-old-murder.html?ref=iraeinhorn | title = Ex-Fugitive Convicted in 25-Year-Old Murder | newspaper = The New York Times | date = October 18, 2002}}.</ref><ref>{{Citation | type = background | url = http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,168382,00.html | title = The Ira Einhorn Case | newspaper = Time | date = July 20, 2001}}.</ref> he became active in [[Green politics|ecological]] groups and was part of the [[counterculture]], [[anti-establishment]], and [[Opposition to the Vietnam War|anti-war]] movements of the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name = MSNBC>{{cite web|url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922 |title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend | publisher = NBC News | accessdate= 2011-04-22}}</ref>  Einhorn participated in the first [[Earth Day]] event in [[Philadelphia]] in 1970, and later claimed to have been instrumental in creating and launching the event,<ref name=MSNBC/> but other event organizers dispute his account.<ref>{{cite web | publisher = AMGOT | url = http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/eday.htm | type = Letter | author = Earth Week Committee of Philadelphia | title = Einhorn | access-date = 2010-04-25 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017152905/http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/eday.htm | archive-date = 2013-10-17 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/04/22/ira-einhorn-not-founder-earth-day/|title=No, Ira Einhorn Didn't Found Earth Day|date=22 April 2015|publisher=phillymag.com}}</ref>\n\n==Murder of Holly Maddux==\nEinhorn had a five-year relationship with Holly Maddux, a graduate of [[Bryn Mawr College]] who was originally from [[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]], [[Texas]]. In 1977, Maddux broke up with Einhorn and went to [[New York City]], where she became involved with Saul Lapidus. On September 9, 1977, Maddux returned to the Philadelphia apartment she had previously shared with Einhorn to collect her belongings (which Einhorn had reportedly threatened to throw out into the street as trash) and was never seen again. Several weeks later, the [[Philadelphia Police Department|Philadelphia police]] questioned Einhorn about her disappearance. He claimed that Maddux had gone out to the neighborhood co-op to buy some [[tofu]] and [[Bean sprouts|sprouts]], and never returned.\n\nEinhorn's initial [[alibi]] came into question when his neighbors began complaining about a foul smell coming from his apartment, which in turn aroused the suspicion of authorities. Eighteen months later, on March 28, 1979, Maddux's [[human decomposition|decomposing]] corpse was found by police in a trunk stored in Einhorn's closet. After finding the body, a police officer reportedly said to Einhorn, \"It looks like we found Holly,\" to which he reportedly replied, \"You found what you found.\" Einhorn's [[bail]] was reduced to $40,000 at the request of his attorney [[Arlen Specter]]; he was released from custody in advance of his trial by paying 10% of the bond's value, or $4,000. This amount was paid by socialite [[Phyllis Lambert]], one of the many people Einhorn had convinced to support him financially.\n\nIn 1981, just days before his murder trial was to begin, Einhorn skipped bail and fled to [[Europe]]. He lived there for the next seventeen years and married a [[Sweden|Swedish]] woman named Annika Flodin. Back in [[Pennsylvania]], as Einhorn had already been [[arraignment|arraigned]], the state convicted him ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' for Maddux's murder in 1996. Einhorn was sentenced to [[life imprisonment|life in prison]] without the possibility of [[parole]].\n\n==Extradition==\nThroughout Ira Einhorn's fugitive flight he was supported by the wealthy Canadian Bronfman family,  heirs to the whisky fortune. Others, friends of the Bronfmans, joined them in supporting Einhorn, indifferent to or doubtful of his murder of his ex-girlfriend Holly.\n\nIn 1997, Einhorn was arrested in [[Champagne-Mouton]], [[France]], where he had been living under the name \"Eug\u00e8ne Mallon\". The [[extradition]] process, however, proved more complex than initially envisioned. Under the extradition treaty between France and the US, either country may refuse extradition under certain circumstances, and Einhorn used multiple avenues to avoid extradition.\n\nAlthough Einhorn was not [[death penalty|sentenced to death]], his defense attorneys argued that he would face the death penalty if he were returned to the US. France, like many countries that have abolished the death penalty, does not extradite defendants to jurisdictions that retain the death penalty without assurance that it will be neither sought nor applied. Pennsylvania authorities pointed out that when the murder occurred, the state did not practice the death penalty and so Einhorn could not be executed because the state and federal constitutions forbid ''[[ex post facto]]'' law. Einhorn's next strategy involved French law and the [[European Court of Human Rights]], which require a new trial when the defendant was tried ''in absentia'' and unable to present his [[defense (law)|defense]]. On this basis, the court of appeals of [[Bordeaux]] rejected the extradition request.\n\nFollowing the court's decision, thirty-five members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] sent a letter to [[President of France|French President]] [[Jacques Chirac]] to ask for Einhorn's extradition. However, under France's doctrine of the [[separation of powers]], which was invoked in this case, the President cannot give orders to courts and does not intervene in extradition affairs. Therefore, in 1998, to secure Einhorn's extradition, the Pennsylvania legislature passed a bill, nicknamed the \"Einhorn Law\", allowing defendants convicted ''in absentia'' to request another trial. In another delay tactic, Einhorn's attorneys criticized the bill as unconstitutional and tried to get the French courts to once again deny the extradition on the grounds that the law would be inapplicable. However, the French court ruled itself unable to evaluate the constitutionality of foreign laws. Another point of friction with the US was that the court freed Einhorn under police supervision, as French laws put restrictions on [[detention of suspects|remand]], the imprisonment of suspects awaiting trial. Einhorn then became the focus of intense surveillance by French police.\n\nThe matter went before [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Lionel Jospin]]; extraditions, after having been approved by courts, must be ordered by the executive. The [[French Green Party]] stated that Einhorn should not be extradited until the issues concerning his case were fully settled.<ref name=\"LesVerts\"><!-- this site no longer exists: {{cite web|url=http://www.les-verts.org/article.php3?id_article=224 |title=Les Verts \u2013 Ira Einhorn extrad\u00e9 }}--> {{cite web|url=http://www.lesverts.fr/spip.php?page=imprimir_articulo&id_article=224|title=Ira Einhorn extrad\u00e9|date=July 20, 2001|publisher=Les Verts|language=french|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026202806/http://www.lesverts.fr/spip.php?page=imprimir_articulo&id_article=224|archivedate=October 26, 2013|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> Jospin rejected the claims and issued an extradition [[decree]]. Einhorn then litigated against the decree before the ''[[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]]'', which ruled against him; again, the Council declined to review the constitutionality of foreign law.<ref name=\"Council of State Ruling\">{{cite web|url= http://www.rajf.org/imprimer.php3?id_article=144 |title= Council of State Ruling}}</ref> He then attempted to slit his own throat to avoid imprisonment<ref name=NYTimes2001>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/13/us/france-agrees-to-extradition-of-culprit-in-killing-in-us.html |title=France Agrees to Extradition Of Culprit in Killing in U.S. | work=The New York Times | date=July 13, 2001}}</ref> and eventually litigated his case before the European Court of Human Rights, which also ruled against him. On July 20, 2001, Einhorn was extradited to the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/us/ex-fugitive-convicted-in-25-year-old-murder.html|title=Ex-Fugitive Convicted in 25-Year-Old Murder|date=18 October 2002|work=AP|via=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Trial and penalty===\nTaking the stand in his own defense, Einhorn claimed that Maddux was murdered by [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agents who attempted to frame him due to his \"investigations\" into the [[Cold War]] and \"[[Psionics|psychotronics]]\".<ref name=Salon>{{cite web |url=http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/10/18/einhorn/index.html |title=Dave Lindorff's 2002 article on the Einhorn trial in ''Salon'' |accessdate=2010-03-31 |date=2002-10-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831230541/http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/10/18/einhorn/index.html |archivedate=2010-08-31 }}</ref> After two hours of deliberation, the jury convicted Einhorn on October 17, 2002, concluding the month-long trial.<ref name=NYTimes/> The following day, he was sentenced to a mandatory life term without the possibility of parole.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thedp.com/index.php/article/2002/10/einhorn_sentenced_to_life_in_prison |title=Einhorn sentenced to life in prison |work=The Daily Pennsylvanian |first=Stephanie |last=Steward |date=October 18, 2002 |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Einhorn began serving his sentence at [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Houtzdale|SCI Houtzdale]]. In April 2016, he was transferred to [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Laurel Highlands|SCI Laurel Highlands]], a minimum security prison that provides care for inmates with health needs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inmatelocator.cor.pa.gov/|title=Inmate Locator|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia|Biography}}\n* [[Crime in Philadelphia]]\n* ''[[The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer]]''\n*[[Earth Day]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Einhorn, Ira. ''78-187880''. (1972) {{ISBN|0-385-06387-3}} Its title is its Library of Congress number.\n*Einhorn, Ira. (August 2005). ''Prelude to Intimacy''. {{ISBN|1-4116-4911-7}}. Einhorn's account of his life underground from the time he fled the United States in early January 1981 until he met his Swedish wife, Annika, in November 1987.\n*[[Steven Levy|Levy, Steven]]. (1988). ''The Unicorn's Secret: Murder in the Age of Aquarius''. {{ISBN|0-13-937830-8}}. Published while Einhorn's whereabouts were unknown.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217203506/http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/lkl8d2.htm Excerpt from Larry King Live] about Einhorn's attempts at denying extradition\n* [http://www.philly.com/philly/hp/art/history_philadelphia_crime.html?next=3&index=32#photo News Photo of the box containing the victim being removed from the house.] (See photographs #35\u00f737.)\n* [http://www.esquire.com/features/ESQ1299-DEC_IRA_EINHORN \"A touch of Eden\"] by [[Russ Baker]], ''Esquire'' December 1, 1999. A series of interviews of Einhorn in France just prior to his extradition.\n* {{IMDb name|1527575}}\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0189593/ The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer] 1999 Movie about Ira Einhorn\n* Documentary series from Court TV (now TruTV) [https://web.archive.org/web/20171006212244/http://filmrise.com/mugshots-ira-einhorn-the-unicorn/ \"MUGSHOTS: Ira Einhorn - The Unicorn\"] episode at ''[[FilmRise]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Einhorn, Ira}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Activists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:American anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Central High School (Philadelphia) alumni]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People extradited to the United States]]\n[[Category:People extradited from France]]\n[[Category:People convicted in absentia]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Ira Einhorn\n| image_name         = Ira Einhorn.png\n| image_caption      = Einhorn's 1979 mugshot and a 2001 mugshot taken upon his return to the U.S.\n| birth_name         = Ira Samuel Einhorn\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1940|05|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|03|1940|05|15}}\n| death_place        = [[Somerset, Pennsylvania|Somerset]], Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| other_names        = The Unicorn Killer, The Unicorn\n| charge             = [[Murder]]\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]]\n| conviction_status  = Incarcerated\n| occupation         =  \n| spouse             =\n| parents            =\n| children           =\n}}\n'''Ira Samuel Einhorn''' (May 15, 1940 \u2013 April 3, 2020), known as '''\"The Unicorn Killer\"''', was an American convicted of murdering his ex-girlfriend, Holly Maddux. On September 9, 1977, Maddux disappeared following a trip to collect her belongings from the apartment she and Einhorn had shared in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Eighteen months later, police found her partially [[mummification|mummified]] body in a trunk in Einhorn's closet.<ref name=compost>{{cite news|last=Melina|first=Remy|title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/#.U_qrdvboct4|agency=NBC News|date=2011-04-21}}</ref>\n\nAfter his arrest, Einhorn fled the country and spent twenty-three years in [[Europe]] before being [[extradition|extradited]] to the US. He took the stand in his own defense, claiming his ex-girlfriend had been killed by [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agents who framed him for the crime because he knew too much about the agency's paranormal military research. He was convicted and served a [[life imprisonment|life sentence]] until his death in prison in April 2020.<ref name=compost/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.6abc.com/amp/ira-einhorn-case-murder-who-was-holly-maddux/6074265/|title=\u201cUnicorn Killer\u201d Ira Einhorn Dies in Prison|work=6abc.com|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis moniker, \"the [[Unicorn]]\", comes from the surname Einhorn, which means \"unicorn\" in [[German language|German]].\n\n==Early life and activism==\nIra Einhorn was born into a middle-class [[Jewish people|Jewish]] family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/the-assimilator/306565/jewish-earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/|title=When Jewish Earth Day Co-Founder Killed, Composted Girlfriend|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/#.Vk4u2CtZjYg|title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend|date=22 April 2011|publisher=}}</ref> As a student at the [[University of Pennsylvania]],<ref name = NYTimes>{{Citation | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/us/ex-fugitive-convicted-in-25-year-old-murder.html?ref=iraeinhorn | title = Ex-Fugitive Convicted in 25-Year-Old Murder | newspaper = The New York Times | date = October 18, 2002}}.</ref><ref>{{Citation | type = background | url = http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,168382,00.html | title = The Ira Einhorn Case | newspaper = Time | date = July 20, 2001}}.</ref> he became active in [[Green politics|ecological]] groups and was part of the [[counterculture]], [[anti-establishment]], and [[Opposition to the Vietnam War|anti-war]] movements of the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name = MSNBC>{{cite web|url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922 |title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend | publisher = NBC News | accessdate= 2011-04-22}}</ref>  Einhorn participated in the first [[Earth Day]] event in [[Philadelphia]] in 1970, and later claimed to have been instrumental in creating and launching the event,<ref name=MSNBC/> but other event organizers dispute his account.<ref>{{cite web | publisher = AMGOT | url = http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/eday.htm | type = Letter | author = Earth Week Committee of Philadelphia | title = Einhorn | access-date = 2010-04-25 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017152905/http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/eday.htm | archive-date = 2013-10-17 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/04/22/ira-einhorn-not-founder-earth-day/|title=No, Ira Einhorn Didn't Found Earth Day|date=22 April 2015|publisher=phillymag.com}}</ref>\n\n==Murder of Holly Maddux==\nEinhorn had a five-year relationship with Holly Maddux, a graduate of [[Bryn Mawr College]] who was originally from [[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]], [[Texas]]. In 1977, Maddux broke up with Einhorn and went to [[New York City]], where she became involved with Saul Lapidus. On September 9, 1977, Maddux returned to the Philadelphia apartment she had previously shared with Einhorn to collect her belongings (which Einhorn had reportedly threatened to throw out into the street as trash) and was never seen again. Several weeks later, the [[Philadelphia Police Department|Philadelphia police]] questioned Einhorn about her disappearance. He claimed that Maddux had gone out to the neighborhood co-op to buy some [[tofu]] and [[Bean sprouts|sprouts]], and never returned.\n\nEinhorn's initial [[alibi]] came into question when his neighbors began complaining about a foul smell coming from his apartment, which in turn aroused the suspicion of authorities. Eighteen months later, on March 28, 1979, Maddux's [[human decomposition|decomposing]] corpse was found by police in a trunk stored in Einhorn's closet. After finding the body, a police officer reportedly said to Einhorn, \"It looks like we found Holly,\" to which he reportedly replied, \"You found what you found.\" Einhorn's [[bail]] was reduced to $40,000 at the request of his attorney [[Arlen Specter]]; he was released from custody in advance of his trial by paying 10% of the bond's value, or $4,000. This amount was paid by socialite [[Phyllis Lambert]], one of the many people Einhorn had convinced to support him financially.\n\nIn 1981, just days before his murder trial was to begin, Einhorn skipped bail and fled to [[Europe]]. He lived there for the next seventeen years and married a [[Sweden|Swedish]] woman named Annika Flodin. Back in [[Pennsylvania]], as Einhorn had already been [[arraignment|arraigned]], the state convicted him ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' for Maddux's murder in 1996. Einhorn was sentenced to [[life imprisonment|life in prison]] without the possibility of [[parole]].\n\n==Extradition==\nThroughout Ira Einhorn's fugitive flight he was supported by the wealthy Canadian Bronfman family,  heirs to the whisky fortune. Others, friends of the Bronfmans, joined them in supporting Einhorn, indifferent to doubtful of his murder of his ex-girlfriend Holly.\n\nIn 1997, Einhorn was arrested in [[Champagne-Mouton]], [[France]], where he had been living under the name \"Eug\u00e8ne Mallon\". The [[extradition]] process, however, proved more complex than initially envisioned. Under the extradition treaty between France and the US, either country may refuse extradition under certain circumstances, and Einhorn used multiple avenues to avoid extradition.\n\nAlthough Einhorn was not [[death penalty|sentenced to death]], his defense attorneys argued that he would face the death penalty if he were returned to the US. France, like many countries that have abolished the death penalty, does not extradite defendants to jurisdictions that retain the death penalty without assurance that it will be neither sought nor applied. Pennsylvania authorities pointed out that when the murder occurred, the state did not practice the death penalty and so Einhorn could not be executed because the state and federal constitutions forbid ''[[ex post facto]]'' law. Einhorn's next strategy involved French law and the [[European Court of Human Rights]], which require a new trial when the defendant was tried ''in absentia'' and unable to present his [[defense (law)|defense]]. On this basis, the court of appeals of [[Bordeaux]] rejected the extradition request.\n\nFollowing the court's decision, thirty-five members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] sent a letter to [[President of France|French President]] [[Jacques Chirac]] to ask for Einhorn's extradition. However, under France's doctrine of the [[separation of powers]], which was invoked in this case, the President cannot give orders to courts and does not intervene in extradition affairs. Therefore, in 1998, to secure Einhorn's extradition, the Pennsylvania legislature passed a bill, nicknamed the \"Einhorn Law\", allowing defendants convicted ''in absentia'' to request another trial. In another delay tactic, Einhorn's attorneys criticized the bill as unconstitutional and tried to get the French courts to once again deny the extradition on the grounds that the law would be inapplicable. However, the French court ruled itself unable to evaluate the constitutionality of foreign laws. Another point of friction with the US was that the court freed Einhorn under police supervision, as French laws put restrictions on [[detention of suspects|remand]], the imprisonment of suspects awaiting trial. Einhorn then became the focus of intense surveillance by French police.\n\nThe matter went before [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Lionel Jospin]]; extraditions, after having been approved by courts, must be ordered by the executive. The [[French Green Party]] stated that Einhorn should not be extradited until the issues concerning his case were fully settled.<ref name=\"LesVerts\"><!-- this site no longer exists: {{cite web|url=http://www.les-verts.org/article.php3?id_article=224 |title=Les Verts \u2013 Ira Einhorn extrad\u00e9 }}--> {{cite web|url=http://www.lesverts.fr/spip.php?page=imprimir_articulo&id_article=224|title=Ira Einhorn extrad\u00e9|date=July 20, 2001|publisher=Les Verts|language=french|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026202806/http://www.lesverts.fr/spip.php?page=imprimir_articulo&id_article=224|archivedate=October 26, 2013|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> Jospin rejected the claims and issued an extradition [[decree]]. Einhorn then litigated against the decree before the ''[[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]]'', which ruled against him; again, the Council declined to review the constitutionality of foreign law.<ref name=\"Council of State Ruling\">{{cite web|url= http://www.rajf.org/imprimer.php3?id_article=144 |title= Council of State Ruling}}</ref> He then attempted to slit his own throat to avoid imprisonment<ref name=NYTimes2001>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/13/us/france-agrees-to-extradition-of-culprit-in-killing-in-us.html |title=France Agrees to Extradition Of Culprit in Killing in U.S. | work=The New York Times | date=July 13, 2001}}</ref> and eventually litigated his case before the European Court of Human Rights, which also ruled against him. On July 20, 2001, Einhorn was extradited to the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/us/ex-fugitive-convicted-in-25-year-old-murder.html|title=Ex-Fugitive Convicted in 25-Year-Old Murder|date=18 October 2002|work=AP|via=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Trial and penalty===\nTaking the stand in his own defense, Einhorn claimed that Maddux was murdered by [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agents who attempted to frame him due to his \"investigations\" into the [[Cold War]] and \"[[Psionics|psychotronics]]\".<ref name=Salon>{{cite web |url=http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/10/18/einhorn/index.html |title=Dave Lindorff's 2002 article on the Einhorn trial in ''Salon'' |accessdate=2010-03-31 |date=2002-10-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831230541/http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/10/18/einhorn/index.html |archivedate=2010-08-31 }}</ref> After two hours of deliberation, the jury convicted Einhorn on October 17, 2002, concluding the month-long trial.<ref name=NYTimes/> The following day, he was sentenced to a mandatory life term without the possibility of parole.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thedp.com/index.php/article/2002/10/einhorn_sentenced_to_life_in_prison |title=Einhorn sentenced to life in prison |work=The Daily Pennsylvanian |first=Stephanie |last=Steward |date=October 18, 2002 |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Einhorn began serving his sentence at [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Houtzdale|SCI Houtzdale]]. In April 2016, he was transferred to [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Laurel Highlands|SCI Laurel Highlands]], a minimum security prison that provides care for inmates with health needs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inmatelocator.cor.pa.gov/|title=Inmate Locator|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia|Biography}}\n* [[Crime in Philadelphia]]\n* ''[[The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer]]''\n*[[Earth Day]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Einhorn, Ira. ''78-187880''. (1972) {{ISBN|0-385-06387-3}} Its title is its Library of Congress number.\n*Einhorn, Ira. (August 2005). ''Prelude to Intimacy''. {{ISBN|1-4116-4911-7}}. Einhorn's account of his life underground from the time he fled the United States in early January 1981 until he met his Swedish wife, Annika, in November 1987.\n*[[Steven Levy|Levy, Steven]]. (1988). ''The Unicorn's Secret: Murder in the Age of Aquarius''. {{ISBN|0-13-937830-8}}. Published while Einhorn's whereabouts were unknown.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217203506/http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/lkl8d2.htm Excerpt from Larry King Live] about Einhorn's attempts at denying extradition\n* [http://www.philly.com/philly/hp/art/history_philadelphia_crime.html?next=3&index=32#photo News Photo of the box containing the victim being removed from the house.] (See photographs #35\u00f737.)\n* [http://www.esquire.com/features/ESQ1299-DEC_IRA_EINHORN \"A touch of Eden\"] by [[Russ Baker]], ''Esquire'' December 1, 1999. A series of interviews of Einhorn in France just prior to his extradition.\n* {{IMDb name|1527575}}\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0189593/ The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer] 1999 Movie about Ira Einhorn\n* Documentary series from Court TV (now TruTV) [https://web.archive.org/web/20171006212244/http://filmrise.com/mugshots-ira-einhorn-the-unicorn/ \"MUGSHOTS: Ira Einhorn - The Unicorn\"