{"title_page": "Joseph de Riquet de Caraman-Chimay (1836\u20131892)", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian politician (1836-1892)}}\n[[File:Joseph de Riquet de Caraman-Chimay (1836-1892) B.jpg|thumb|Portrait c. 1890]]\n'''Marie-''Joseph''-Guy-Henry-Philippe de Riquet de Caraman, 18th Prince de Chimay''' (9 October 1836, [[Ch\u00e2teau de Menars]], France \u2013 29 March 1892, [[Brussels]], Belgium), was a Belgian diplomat and politician. He was notable as [[Belgian Ambassador to the Holy See|Ambassador to the Holy See]] (1846-1847), governor of the [[province of Hainaut]] (1870-1878) and [[Foreign Minister (Belgium)|Foreign Minister]] (1884-1892).\n\n==Life==\nHis parents were [[Joseph de Riquet de Caraman-Chimay (1808-1886)|Joseph de Riquet de Caraman]], 17th [[Prince de Chimay]], and [[\u00c9milie Pellapra]]. His own six children included [[Joseph, Prince de Caraman-Chimay]], Prince Alexandre (who married [[Mathilde Stuyvesant]]), and [[\u00c9lisabeth, Countess Greffulhe|\u00c9lisabeth]] (who married the [[Henry Greffulhe|Count of Greffulhe]]).\n\nHe also gave private concerts, with him on violin and his wife on piano. In memory of one of these at which he had assisted, [[Franz Liszt]] dedicated a mass to Caraman-Chimay<ref>Anne de Coss\u00e9-Brissac, La Comtesse Greffulhe, coll. \u00ab Terre des femmes \u00bb, Perrin, Paris, 1991, p. 34.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20161113015527/http://www.chateaudechimay.be/?page_id=761\n* [http://www.odis.be/lnk/en/PS_27434 Joseph de Riquet de Caraman-Chimay] in [https://www.odis.eu ODIS - Online Database for Intermediary Structures] \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caraman-Chimay, Joseph de Riquet}}\n[[Category:Belgian diplomats]]\n[[Category:19th-century Belgian politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Belgium to the Holy See]]\n[[Category:Princes of Chimay|Joseph]]\n[[Category:1836 births]]\n[[Category:1892 deaths]]\n\n\n{{France-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belgian politician (1836-1892)}}\n[[File:Joseph de Riquet de Caraman-Chimay (1836-1892) B.jpg|thumb|Portrait c. 1890]]\n'''Marie-''Joseph''-Guy-Henry-Philippe de Riquet de Caraman, 18th Prince de Chimay''' (9 October 1836, [[Ch\u00e2teau de Menars]], France \u2013 29 March 1892, [[Brussels]], Belgium), was a Belgian diplomat and politician. He was notable as [[Belgian Ambassador to the Holy See|Ambassador to the Holy See]] (1846-1847), governor of the [[province of Hainaut]] (1870-1878) and [[Foreign Minister (Belgium)|Foreign Minister]] (1884-1892).\n\nHis parents were [[Joseph de Riquet de Caraman-Chimay (1808-1886)|Joseph de Riquet de Caraman]], 17th [[Prince de Chimay]], and [[\u00c9milie Pellapra]]. His own six children included [[Joseph, Prince de Caraman-Chimay]] and [[\u00c9lisabeth, Countess Greffulhe|\u00c9lisabeth]], who married the [[Henry Greffulhe|Count of Greffulhe]].\n\nHe also gave private concerts, with him on violin and his wife on piano. In memory of one of these at which he had assisted, [[Franz Liszt]] dedicated a mass to Caraman-Chimay<ref>Anne de Coss\u00e9-Brissac, La Comtesse Greffulhe, coll. \u00ab Terre des femmes \u00bb, Perrin, Paris, 1991, p. 34.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20161113015527/http://www.chateaudechimay.be/?page_id=761\n* [http://www.odis.be/lnk/en/PS_27434 Joseph de Riquet de Caraman-Chimay] in [https://www.odis.eu ODIS - Online Database for Intermediary Structures] \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caraman-Chimay, Joseph de Riquet}}\n[[Category:Belgian diplomats]]\n[[Category:19th-century Belgian politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Belgium to the Holy See]]\n[[Category:Princes of Chimay|Joseph]]\n[[Category:1836 births]]\n[[Category:1892 deaths]]\n\n\n{{France-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DACC23", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_de_Riquet_de_Caraman-Chimay_(1836%E2%80%931892)"}
{"title_page": "Joseph ben Mordechai Gershon", "text_new": "'''Joseph ben Mordechai Gershon HaKohen Ka\"tz''' (1510 in [[Cracow]] &ndash; 1591) was a [[kohen]] by birth, rabbi and [[Talmudist]], began his studies in the Talmud at an early age, and became the [[rosh yeshivah]] founded for him by his father-in-law. The many pupils who attended this school soon made him famous for his scholarship; and his views on religious questions were widely sought. [[Solomon Luria]] was one of his correspondents.\n\nJoseph was the author of \"She'erit Yosef\" (Cracow, 1590), containing [[responsa]] and discussions on various rabbinical subjects, as well as a commentary on the \"[[Mordecai ben Hillel|Mordechai]]\" [[Tract (literature)|tractates]] [[Nezikin]], [[Berakhot (Talmud)|Berakot]], and [[Mo'ed]]. In the [[preface]] the author states that he published this work at the request of his sons, Tanhuma and Aaron Moses, who were members of the [[Jewish]] community of Cracow. He also corrected the manuscript from which was printed the \"Aggudah\" of [[Alexandri HaKohain]] of [[Frankfurt]].\n\n==Jewish Encyclopedia bibliography==\n*[http://hebrewbooks.org/1195 She'rith Yosef]\n* I. M. Zunz, 'Ir ha-zedek, p.&nbsp;23, Lemberg, 1874;\n* Rabinowitz, Ha'arot we-Tikunim, p.&nbsp;6, Lyck, 1875;\n* [[Haim Nathan Dembitzer|Dembitzer]], Kelilat Yoft, p.&nbsp;4b, Cracow, 1888;\n* B. Friedberg, Gesch. der Hebr\u00e4ischen Typographie in Krakau, p.&nbsp;8, ib. 1900.S.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n*{{JewishEncyclopedia\n|article=Joseph ben Mordecai Gershon Ha-Kohen\n|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=501&letter=J\n|author=[[Solomon Schechter]] and Bernhard Friedberg}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gershon, Joseph Ben Mordechai}}\n[[Category:1510 births]]\n[[Category:1591 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish rabbis]]\n[[Category:Kohanim writers of Rabbinic literature]]\n[[Category:People from Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:16th-century rabbis]]\n", "text_old": "Rabbi '''Joseph ben Mordechai Gershon HaKohen Ka\"tz''' (1510 in [[Cracow]] &ndash; 1591), a [[kohen]] by birth, rabbi and [[Talmudist]], began his studies in the Talmud at an early age, and became the [[rosh yeshivah]] founded for him by his father-in-law. The many pupils who attended this school soon made him famous for his scholarship; and his views on religious questions were widely sought. [[Solomon Luria]] was one of his correspondents.\n\nJoseph was the author of \"She'erit Yosef\" (Cracow, 1590), containing [[responsa]] and discussions on various rabbinical subjects, as well as a commentary on the \"[[Mordecai ben Hillel|Mordechai]]\" [[Tract (literature)|tractates]] [[Nezikin]], [[Berakhot (Talmud)|Berakot]], and [[Mo'ed]]. In the [[preface]] the author states that he published this work at the request of his sons, Tanhuma and Aaron Moses, who were members of the [[Jewish]] community of Cracow. He also corrected the manuscript from which was printed the \"Aggudah\" of [[Alexandri HaKohain]] of [[Frankfurt]].\n\n==Jewish Encyclopedia bibliography==\n*[http://hebrewbooks.org/1195 She'rith Yosef]\n* I. M. Zunz, 'Ir ha-zedek, p.&nbsp;23, Lemberg, 1874;\n* Rabinowitz, Ha'arot we-Tikunim, p.&nbsp;6, Lyck, 1875;\n* [[Haim Nathan Dembitzer|Dembitzer]], Kelilat Yoft, p.&nbsp;4b, Cracow, 1888;\n* B. Friedberg, Gesch. der Hebr\u00e4ischen Typographie in Krakau, p.&nbsp;8, ib. 1900.S.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n*{{JewishEncyclopedia\n|article=Joseph ben Mordecai Gershon Ha-Kohen\n|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=501&letter=J\n|author=[[Solomon Schechter]] and Bernhard Friedberg}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gershon, Joseph Ben Mordechai}}\n[[Category:1510 births]]\n[[Category:1591 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish rabbis]]\n[[Category:Kohanim writers of Rabbinic literature]]\n[[Category:People from Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:16th-century rabbis]]\n", "name_user": "TRM001", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar/sentence fluency", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_ben_Mordechai_Gershon"}
{"title_page": "Chatuna Gogaladze", "text_new": "{{Expand language|topic=|langcode=ka|otherarticle=\u10ee\u10d0\u10d7\u10e3\u10dc\u10d0 \u10d2\u10dd\u10d2\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10eb\u10d4|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Minister of Environment Khatuna Gogaladze (2013).jpeg|thumb|right|Gogaladze in 2013]]\n'''Chatuna Gogaladze''' ({{lang-ka|\u10ee\u10d0\u10d7\u10e3\u10dc\u10d0 \u10d2\u10dd\u10d2\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10eb\u10d4}}; born 18 April 1970) is a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] politician. Between 2012 and 2014 she was [[Ministry of Environment and Natural Resources Protection of Georgia|Minister of Environment and Natural Resources Protection]] in the cabinets of [[Bidzina Ivanishvili]] and [[Irakli Garibashvili]].<ref name=\"ministry\">{{cite web |title=About Ministry: Minister |url=http://moe.gov.ge/index.php?sec_id=7&lang_id=ENG |publisher=Minister of Environment and Natural Resources Protection of Georgia |accessdate=2 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730101915/http://moe.gov.ge/index.php?sec_id=7&lang_id=ENG |archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe has a degree in biology from the [[Ivane Javakhishvili Tbilisi State University]] and masters degrees in Public Affairs from [[Indiana University Bloomington]], and in Environmental Sciences and Policy from [[Central European University]], Budapest.<ref name=ministry />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |title=\u10ee\u10d0\u10d7\u10e3\u10dc\u10d0 \u10d2\u10dd\u10d2\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10eb\u10d4 (1970) |url=http://www.nplg.gov.ge/bios/en/00006574/ |website=Biographical Dictionary of Georgia |publisher=National Parliamentary Library of Georgia |accessdate=2 April 2020|language=Georgian}} \n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gogaladze, Chatuna}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Georgia (country)]] <!-- non-diffusing subcat -->\n\n\n{{Georgia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Expand language|topic=|langcode=ka|otherarticle=\u10ee\u10d0\u10d7\u10e3\u10dc\u10d0 \u10d2\u10dd\u10d2\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10eb\u10d4|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Minister of Environment Khatuna Gogaladze (2013).jpeg|thumb|right|Gogaladze in 2013]]\n'''Chatuna Gogaladze''' ({{lang-ka|\u10ee\u10d0\u10d7\u10e3\u10dc\u10d0 \u10d2\u10dd\u10d2\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10eb\u10d4}}; born 18 April 1970) is a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] politician. Between 2012 and 2014 she was [[Ministry of Environment and Natural Resources Protection of Georgia|Minister of Environment and Natural Resources Protection]] in the cabinet of [[Bidzina Ivanishvili]] and [[Irakli Garibashvili]].<ref name=\"ministry\">{{cite web |title=About Ministry: Minister |url=http://moe.gov.ge/index.php?sec_id=7&lang_id=ENG |publisher=Minister of Environment and Natural Resources Protection of Georgia |accessdate=2 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730101915/http://moe.gov.ge/index.php?sec_id=7&lang_id=ENG |archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe has a degree in biology from the [[Ivane Javakhishvili Tbilisi State University]] and masters degrees in Public Affairs from [[Indiana University Bloomington]], and in Environmental Sciences and Policy from [[Central European University]], Budapest.<ref name=ministry />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |title=\u10ee\u10d0\u10d7\u10e3\u10dc\u10d0 \u10d2\u10dd\u10d2\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10eb\u10d4 (1970) |url=http://www.nplg.gov.ge/bios/en/00006574/ |website=Biographical Dictionary of Georgia |publisher=National Parliamentary Library of Georgia |accessdate=2 April 2020|language=Georgian}} \n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gogaladze, Chatuna}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Georgia (country)]] <!-- non-diffusing subcat -->\n\n\n{{Georgia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_u